ynamics of Sino-Western relations during the formative century before the First Opium War (1839-1842). He highlights the centrality of law to modern imperial ideology and politics and brings new insight to the origins of comparative Chinese law in the West, the First Opium War, and foreign extraterritoriality in China. The shifting balance of economic and political power formed and transformed knowledge of China and Chinese law in different contact zones. Chen argues that recovering the variegated and contradictory roles of Chinese law in Western "modernization" helps provincialize the subsequent Euro-Americentric discourse of global modernity. Chen draws attention to important yet underanalyzed sites in which imperial sovereignty, national identity, cultural tradition, or international law and order were defined and restructured. His valuable case studies show how constructed differences between societies were hardened into cultural or racial boundaries and then politicized to rationalize international conflicts and hierarchy."--Publisher's description.00aDa Qing lü.07aDa Qing lü.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01379237 0aExterritoriality. 0aSovereignty. 0aCriminal lawzChinaxHistory. 0aJustice, Administration ofzChina. 7aCriminal law.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00883328 7aExterritoriality.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00918952 7aJustice, Administration of.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00985154 7aLaw.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00993678 0aSociological jurisprudencezChinaxHistory. 7aSovereignty.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01127379 0aLawzChinaxHistory. 7aRecht2gnd 7aChinabild2gnd 7aSociological jurisprudence.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01123856 7aWestliche Welt2gnd 7aChina.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01206073 7aChina2gnd 7aHistory.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01411628 0aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University.423Book review (H-Net)uhttp://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=46754 46264-00c�2016006630-00aDa Qing L�u.  aYBP Library ServicesbYANKn15013204  aYBP Library 